t was common during your youth, making you feel some nostalgia about your past. <i>“So how it is?”</i> You tell her that she was right about the humbling experience. <i>“Glad to hear that, although I sense that this is not the first time that you taste something like this… I’ve seen rich people before trying for the first time food that doesn't cost what a poor man earns in a year and definitely their reactions were different.”</i> \n\nYou tell her that she is right,that actually you’ve been living in the forest since you were a child, because of the assassination of your father by the late lord, who was your uncle. <i>“O-oh… I am sorry, I didn’t knew about it… People here doesn’t want or can talk much about you, so I apologize for being so insensitive.”</i> You say that she shouldn’t worry much about it, you barely remember anything about that, or the city, although you are glad that your mother returned recently. <i>“Seriously?! That sounds great! That must be the wish of the Gods for you to have that luck!”</i> You aren’t so sure about that, considering the situation of your mother, but probably you should leave that for another day.\n\nTo change the topic you ask about her, and what’s her story. <i>“About me? Where to start… I am from the Viceroyalty of Tzime, a capital city in the middle of the jungle. The place is like a veeery big fortress, without doubt the second largest after the citadel. That reign was fighting for the control of the island against the citadel, but as you may guess, they ultimately lost the war. In any case, I am an orphan, and I’ve lived with the church since I can remember. They taught me everything I know, and shortly before the plague I moved to the neighboring city, Ku-Jiang, where I served as an acolyte until not long ago.”</i> After these words, she pauses, as if know she had to remember and talk about bad memories. \n\n<i>“When the plague started, well… Those were very confusing times, but long story short, pretty much every city got isolated after it, with little to not trade, and there was no veracity in any news from another city since most people that actually travel end up corrupted themselves.”</i> You ask if that is the case with her <i>“W-what? N-no! Of course not! Do I look corrupted to you?”</i> You shrug, saying that you are no expert on the topic, she shakes her head and rejects your question, but you ask her if that’s not what a corrupt person would do. She sighs, frustrated <i>“I promise we can talk about that another day but… Let me finish my story tonight”</i> Fine, you apologize for interrupting her story. <i>“It’s fine. Where I was? Ah right… Yes, I those were some harsh times, we lost a lot of people during those days to the plague, but we kept our hopes high and I kept learning so I could become a priestess someday. I guess I could talk about so many anecdotes about those times, but this is the substance of it. A couple of months before I came we had news that the church in this place was destroyed and the priest ran disappeared, and I offered myself volunteer to come here and preach the word, since the church was reluctant to send some by their own. And… That’s actually how I became a priestess too, since they ordained me just a couple of weeks before my departure.”</i> \n\nIt is impossible for you to hide your surprise and skepticism about this. She gives you a not-so-serious angry face in reaction <i>“I know what you may be thinking, but although my title is new, remember that I’ve been with the church since I was a child, I know everything that there is to know about religious matters.”</i> You tell her that that’s true, but managing a church is more than theology: Is politics, is charisma, is to be able to take hard choices. She is about to answer, but stops before it’s too late. After a pause, she continues <i>“You may be right… I lack that experience, and… Yeah, remember I said earlier? You screw up while learning?… But I don't want to disappoint you nor the city, 